ce:section.ce:para:
Another type of fullerene, i.e., boron nitride (BN) nanoclusters, was explored by Hosseini et al. for their efficacy as anode materials in LIBs, using DFT [104]. Their findings revealed that on encapsulating fluoride within the B12N12 fullerene (Fig. 8B), the electrochemical cell voltage (V

                              cell
                           ) dramatically increased from 1.09 V to 3.07 V. This significant improvement not only highlighted the unique advantages of fullerene structures but also demonstrated enhanced lithium diffusion capabilities within the BN nanocluster. This enhancement in lithium diffusion and electrochemical performance positions BN fullerenes, particularly the fluoride-encapsulated B12N12 variant, as superior to other materials like carbon nanotubes and C24 fullerene.
